In this game, you will learn what version control is.\nYou will use Git commands to operate action during the game.

2. The purpose of using each Git command, and how to use them.

column17: Next, please execute '<color=#CF001C>git init</color>'\nat your project location to create your first Git management system.
Well done! \r\nAfter executing the 'git init' command,\r\na new folder appeared in your project location.
This command creates a folder named '.git' at the specified location.
This folder is 'hidden' in the computer system,\nmeaning you do not need to modify its contents directly.\nInstead, you will use various Git commands to interact with it.
.git' is the core of the entire Git system.\r\nIt contains important information related to the project, \r\nsuch as versions of submissions, authors, time, etc.
Without the '.git' folder, most Git commands cannot operate normally.
Now, let me briefly introduce the three areas that are contained in Git:
First is the 'Working Directory.' \r\nThis area is actually the project location you chose.
All files in the 'Working Directory' are tracked by Git, \r\nwhich is the 'Ongoing Project' folder.
Next is the 'Staging Area.' \r\nThis area acts as a bridge between the 'Working Directory' and the '.git' folder.
You can push file modification contents\nfrom the 'Working Directory' to the 'Staging Area'.
Then move the confirmed files to the '.git' to create a record.
Finally, the 'Repository.' \r\nThe management system created on your local computer is called the 'Local Repository.'
In fact, the 'Repository' is the '.git' folder.
In the upcoming stages, \r\nwe will introduce in more detail the 'Staging Area' and 'Local Repository,' \r\nand operate them using Git commands.
With this operation, \r\nyou have successfully achieved the simulation scenario's objective.

Welcome to the 'Introduction to Version Control and Git' stage!
In this stage, we will focus on explaining concepts without practical operations.\r\nHowever, in the end, theres a quiz to enhance your understanding.
Correct answers will give you 1000 points.\nIncorrect answers will not get any points.

There are four chapters in this stage:
1. Review the Stage 1
2. What is Version Control?
3. What is Git?
4. Summary
At the end of each chapter, you can choose whether to continue to the next chapter.
If you have already taken a break and want to continue, please click here to learn.
In Stage 1, we used the 'backup file' method to complete the midterm presentation.
Although this method is direct and fast, \r\nit can cause problems when dealing with more complex presentations or projects.
First, if theres a large number of backup files during development, \r\nit will be difficult to track the differences between files.
If a serious error occurs and you have to go back to the previous versions, \r\nyou will spend a lot of time on fixing errors.
Second, your work environment becomes messy \r\nbecause of multiple backup files.
You might even encounter situations like:\n1. Developed the content on old versions of files\n2. Overwriting the current development file while backing up files.
To avoid these issues, \r\nwe can use a version control system to help us manage projects.
First, let's get to know what is version control.
Version control is one of the main roles in software development.\nBut is not limited to programming-related fields.
In fact, if theres a project that requires long-term operation and development.\r\nIt can be effectively managed with version control.
The main goal of version control is to better manage changes in files. \r\nIt records every modification during the development.

1. History Tracking: 
It allows you to view every change made to files, 
including who made the changes, when they were made, 
and the specific content of the changes.
For example, graphic designers or web designers might modify images several times while editing.\nIn this scenario, version control can be appropriate to help people manage the images.
2. Rollback Function: \r\nIf you encounter errors or need to go back to the previous version, \r\nversion control can easily return to a previous version without affecting the current development.
3. Branch Management: \r\nIt allows you to create branches for development, \r\nand lets different features be developed at the same time without interference.
The benefits of version control above,\r\nwe will further understand and practically operate in later stages.\r
After understanding what version control is, let's learn about Git.
Git is a powerful version control tool, \r\nits highly popular in software development.
Users will operate version control functions through \nexecuting Git commands in the Command Line.
Here are some advantages of using Git:
1. Team Collaboration: \r\nGit allows team members to develop a project at the same time without interfering with each other's work.\r\nAnd members can easily merge files.
2. Branch Strategy: \r\nGit's branch management feature smoothens the project development process. \r\nYou can create different branches, each focused on specific goals.
Once the development branches are complete, they can be merged into the main branch.\nIt enhances project stability.
3. Version Tracking: \r\nEvery file submission is recorded and stored in Git.\r\nYou can easily view each submission content.

4. Easy to Learn:
Even if you are not a programmer or never touched programming,
Git's concepts are relatively simple. 
You can execute simple Git commands to control the system.
In this game, Git commands are adjusted.\nWe will focus on practical commands and remove difficult ones.
In conclusion, version control significantly enhances project development efficiency and organizes content management.
For historical records and version tracking features,\nwe can clearly see the differences between file versions.
The rollback function allows us to go back to the previous version, \r\nit helps us view historical content and fix problems.
The branching system increases stability and efficiency for project development.
Finally, version control supports team collaboration, \r\nallowing team members to develop features together and \r\nintegrate completed content into the project.
After understanding what version control and Git are,\nlet's have a quiz.

column17: Next, let's simulate the background story for this stage.
After setting up the simulation, \r\nwe'll review the use of the 'Staging Area'.
The 'Staging Area' plays an important role in the Git system, \r\nIt acts as a bridge between the 'Working Directory' and the 'Repository'.
After modifying files in the 'Working Directory', \r\nyou move them to the 'Staging Area' using Git commands.
Once you moved all the changes, \r\nwe'll use another Git command to store all the modifications in the 'Repository'.
The 'Repository' combines them into a record known as a 'commit', \r\nit means we create a new version.

Now, let's understand the problem we are currently facing.
Look at the branch list.\nYou will find the 'Detached' keyword has been added to the HEAD.\nAnd all commits in the field are transparent.
In the Git system,\nthis condition is known as '<color=#CF001C>Detached HEAD</color>'.\nIt means the current HEAD is not pointing to any branch.
When executing 'git checkout commit ID',\nHEAD points to the specified commit.\nIt leads to a '<color=#CF001C>Detached HEAD</color>' situation.
Although HEAD points to the 3rd commit,\nwhich is also the latest commit in the 'master' branch.\nBut HEAD is not actually pointing to the 'master' branch.
After clicking on this commit,\nyou will find that the branch field is no longer 'HEAD -> master'.

Welcome to the 'Git Branching Basics Tutorial' stage!
In the 'Branch Management' theme stage,\nwe will learn about Git's branch system.\nAnd achieve the goals of the simulated scenario through commands and windows.
First, let's review the advantages of the branch system for project management.
Branches in Git are a powerful and practical feature.\nWe can create branches with different names and purposes.
For example, use 'Branch A' to develop new features,\n'Branch B' to fix errors in the project,\nand the main branch (master) to wait for other branches to achieve their goals.
When a team collaborates on a project,\nthese branches can be assigned to different team members.
The branch environment provides an independent development workspace,\nwhere branches do not interfere with each other.
Even if 'Branch A' causes problems in the project,\nwe only need to delete or modify 'Branch A'.\nThe 'master' branch will not be affected.
The branch system brings flexibility and stability to project management.

column17: Welcome to the 'Creating Your First Remote Repository' stage!
In the 'Remote Management' theme stage,\nwe'll learn how to operate a remote repository.\nAnd accomplish objectives through commands and windows.
Before we begin,\nlet's first understand the benefits of using\nremote repositories for project management.
For simple, small projects,\ndeveloping on a local computer may be enough.
However, using a remote repository allows you to upload content to a server.\nIt can back up your project.
This is particularly useful if your local repository becomes unusable due to an accident.\nThe remote repository can help you recover your development progress.
Moreover, uploading your project to the internet\nmeans you can develop on different computers.
One of the greatest advantages of remote repositories is:\nIt supports team-based project development.
Team members can get the project repository on their computers.
They develop it locally and upload changes to the remote server.\nThis process enhances project development efficiency.
Understood the advantages of remote repositories,\nlet's start this stage.

In this stage, we will learn about:\n1. Reviewing Pull Requests.\n2. Merging Pull Requests.
Before we start,\nlet's review what we learned in the previous stage.

On the Git service platform,\nwe created our first Pull Request.

In this stage,\nwe will play the role of a reviewer,\nproviding modification suggestions to developers and approving pull requests.

column17: Next, let's simulate the background for this stage.
After setting up the stage,\nplease open the 'Browser' window.
We will view Pull Requests created by other developers\nfrom the Git service platform.
Alright, after entering the Git service platform,\nlet's learn how to review a Pull Request.
First, switch to the 'Pull Requests' tab\nto view all the ongoing requests.
Currently, there is an ongoing pull request.\nPlease click on this request to enter its detailed page.
From the title and created message of the Pull Request,\nwe learn that team member A is responsible for adding content to 'README.md'.\nIt will tell the teacher the purpose of creating the project.
To review the file changes made by the request creator,\nplease switch to the 'Files Changed' tab.
In the tab,\nit shows the file changes made by team member A.
This request only modified the content of the 'README.md' file,\nso we can only see the changes to this file.
The first column of each line shows the file content of the Base branch,\nand the second column shows the content of the Compare branch.
Based on the developer's modifications,\nthree kinds of colors will be applied to the lines.
White' means the content is the same in both branches.\n'Red' means content that has been deleted.\n'Green' means added content.
The developer deleted the default title of 'README.md'\nand replaced it with a web page title.\nThen added the reason for creating the website in the file content.
However, if you look closer,\nthere's a typo that appears in the last line.
Now, let's try to tell the developer to correct the typo.
Move the mouse to the line that needs to be changed.\nThen click the left button to add a modification suggestion.
After selecting the correct position,\nthe game will automatically create a modification suggestion.
But please note.\nWhen the message box is created, it shows 'Pending.'\nThis means that the message box is only a draft and is not visible to others yet.
To complete the modification suggestion,\nplease click the 'Review Changes' button\nto display the Pending message in the Pull Request.
Clicked the 'Review Changes' button,\nthere's a message input box that will pop up.
Please enter your suggested content in the input field.\nTo point out the content that needs modification and your opinion.
Then, choose the appropriate comment type\nfrom the following options.
If you want to request the developer to make changes,\nplease select 'Request Changes'.
This will update the merge status area to 'Unresolved Conversation.'\nThe developer needs to resolve this conversation\nso we can continue the merge.
After completing the above steps,\nplease click the 'Submit Review' button\nto submit your review comment.

After refreshing the page,\nyou will find that the conversation box has collapsed.
Expanding it,\nyou will see that the developer has responded to your suggestion\nand fixed the typo.

Reviewing the last line of 'README.md',\nyou'll notice that the typo has been corrected,\nand there is no need to change or add to this file.

Next, please click the 'Review Changes' button\nto approve this pull request.
In the pop-up message box,\nplease fill in a message explaining why you are approving this pull request.
Then, choose 'Approve' from the options below,\nmeans you agree with this merge.
